Last Blood Duel: MP3 Players vs. Cellphones
We will advise how to choose
While almost every cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
From this it is clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons to get an autonomous reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all these musical products do not come out as LP and from a qualitative point of view for this there is not even an objective reason.
If, however, hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls are crowded on your shelves, at least you dream of it.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here, too, the price and quality categories exist.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend for an 8 thousand kroner player, as well as a Pink Floyd fan perhaps hardly digests the market's twenty kroner caps.
Two extremes between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is the battery life that decides.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, but they don't even accidentally do cell phones.
There is no other current device as universal as the cell phone.
Next to the primary functions, phone and text, can read music and video, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe even can navigate.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle that no refrigerator can make the grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the cell phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone and the sooner the on-screen indicator will require the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than twelve hours,usually, and much less.
In this sense music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for the cheap uncounted cell phones that can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add to it, from time to time, some calls, get to work for safety another charger, this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
But you won't have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours at continuous functionality with a recharge.
A further problem exists when downloading music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of devices have the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Certainly the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory players are able to do it without adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, except for a few exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create themselves a multimedia library sorted by the names of the performers, album name, genre or by user classification.
Some devices only reproduce the folder tree structure, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device you are especially interested in battery strength, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs and clearly ease of use.
If you mainly need music as a background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram you just need a mobile phone that reads MP3.
This now succeeds, clearly to any cell phone.
You don't have to worry too much about what formats the cell phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players all support them, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most popular ones, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
It is less the AAC (format used by the Apple company and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet network, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service already could be a valid argument for buying a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is poor and is limited, usually, only to hits of the moment of the radio.
Prices aren't exactly low.
But it is generally assumed that this very mode of music sales (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phone behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to a little something goes through their pocket while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
However, it also depends on this, if you always carry the headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will, for many, be the price.
Cheaper ones normally cost less than 3,000 kroner.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an input for the common headphones.
The best and most technically equipped mobile phones and even with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
On the other hand, the advantage of the readers is, besides others, the easy handling.
Simpler ones not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) really make it anyone to handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally bumping the start of the mobile internet network and consequently of a giant bill for data transmission.
What appliance to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (of the M2 type, microSD etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, which fell within the 2 000 kroner.
But be careful
The basic models support only cards with the maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones make it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners take preferably specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of service so it comes close to the same MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson has come a long way in this regard, whose smartphones in the walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above brands provide you with the same service and price category up to 4 000 kroner, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery strength (commonly 15 hours, in principle up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
Something is still missing here – a virtual operator that forces traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't miss it for a long time.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day, it was also confirmed by T, who pointed out that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regularisation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that would really like to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, he also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council, Pavel Dvosek, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network no longer likely has many possibilities. (Of the rest it would perhaps be difficult now to find other frequencies).
But there is still another possibility -the virtual operator.
The very entry of virtual operators into the market has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices sounded in Britain as we do.
It has proved, however, that the place for such operators is there and that they can be truly successful.
At the end of the day, we don't have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which U:fon belongs in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to actually work, he needs many fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry with them, i.e., relatively high expenses for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the more restricted service offer
So for example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows it can be a pretty good move even betting on a group-target no small.
This operator is specifically targeting men, so to speak.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Epick doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Plus from a service point of view it's relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, mobile network operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have much expectation.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries in our area," said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studnickov, the press spokesman for the financial group Penta.
So he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this thought.
Rather on the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now, he has not been hiding his interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefanika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner the better.
We have negotiated repeatedly on this possibility with all Czech operators of the mobile network.
We have already been able to progress in negotiations with some of them," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will have to have it perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, around its creation stands an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this time we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
Until now no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sr.e. of the press section of Telefònika O2.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by the other operators.
T-Mobil press spokesman Martina Kemrov, added in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both of us, on which it is possible to continue to build."
He adds: "A virtual operator will hardly appear in the T-Mobil network by the end of the year.
At this time we will have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it would be possible to consider it on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its own 3G license requests.
He adds Miroslav Epick: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators and this is especially in the context of sharing expenses and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
The competent authorities -with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, it would lead to lower prices and thereby a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around U:fon creation testify that when operators care about a thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing against T in the period of U:fon's creation towards T-Mobile's company.
This testifies to the public access information from the web pages of ?T?.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which to not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov? remarked: "The competition environment of the mobile phone market has been little enhanced beyond that with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place on him and especially on his high-demand services."
However, the complete disinterest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies is quite surprising.
This is not just about the attitude of the T, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic – unlike Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position towards the whole problem.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristi , of the .OHS external relations section, in the answer to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
Instead by the office that has to defend the interest of consumers and also deal with the fact that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristi?n Chalupa adds: " Abroad where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of OHS.
Truly shocking throughout the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence, arises on its own.
Just as the identical price of gasoline for all petrol stations is without doubt the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its behaviour in the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecom regulator," Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by _________, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has – in the end logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it has to be dominant by force.
But even if we don't admit this argument, for OHS it should be a minimum alert that three mobile operators proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Unloading responsibility to T in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick by which OHS keeps itself out of the whole thing.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the expansion of the rights to telecommunications in the field of economic competition until the recently approved update of the telecommunications law, despite the fact that, from this many experts expected the situation to improve.
This is something the representatives of OHS need to know more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
It can be done, when no one looks
While without us noticing it, the operation of such pseudo-virtual operators remains, some of which even exist in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists of mobile services but are only partially public.
These are usually the companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company towards the operator appears as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer then receives special pricing offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar presale.
"If the cases mentioned are presented, of which we will be interested, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions, and could result in the conclusion of the cooperation with that company", answered the question in question Martina Kemrov.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends itself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a not indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav ?epick? warns about possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
These also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, therefore they cannot dispose in full of it as the regular customers of mobile operators "
But that's exactly what should be a weird little bit at the "T".
In addition, another issue opens up for OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that OHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said in the text several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a considerable drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small market, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in developed countries, regulatory bodies have intervened to defend not mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and non-formal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and others joined him.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators throw the whole case from one to the other like a hot potato.
In our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases is more than comfortable for him.
But let's not throw in the towel.
If the background information is right and the virtual operator will appear to us really soon, the Czech mobile phone market will start up again.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only it would be difficult for OHS to remain impassive to the rejection (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
