In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the extended theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the huge, lies the quiet city where pride and the complications of the African-American experience enter life.
Eatonville, the country's first all-black incorporated town and home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect to Hurston, Harlem Renaissance's most famous writer.
Yet in many ways, the city he described - and which makes tourists stop by understanding it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers' Project - remains a separate place.
He is as independent, dignified and private as he was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who "knowing so little about us, does not know what is being lost."
Even now, in a year when a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called for an opening speech on race, many here remain wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very cautious about how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black takeover and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shade of the oak trees of the rural culture of southern blacks - sometimes disdained, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And concern for Eatonville's imagination really began with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Rout 17, a road running through the often forgotten center of Florida into a scenario of black history and human drama
Low as a bass in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Out of the street to the left," he wrote "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could just read and write."
She also mentioned the widow's new husband Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever suits the passing rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it as it was," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls who Hurston immortalizes by quoting men who sing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds, "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a vibrant eccentric who frequently returned to her family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston swooped into the city, he habitually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing trousers in a city that even today boasts of dignified clothing.
Many inhabitants were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others sneered.
"People were always very happy to see Zora," said Mr. Franklin.
But, he added, rocking in his chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unplated grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no major memorial ceremonies, and no major conference.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change occurred in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed La Interstate 4 across the western edge of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, in addition to other things, had ended its idyllic isolation of the community
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community's doorstep.
"During that time, a group of white boys, they came and threw oranges and things at people sitting on one side," says Mr. Franklin.
"In fact we had a girl who was killed by that one time.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race".
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, despite having been positive in some respects, dilutes the cohesion of Eatonville and jeopardizes the confidence of its young people.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember this - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher...- I mean, there's a cultural divide there," said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and created room for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as he did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines such as: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston's license-free grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit bookstore shelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had drawn the limelight again.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning in 1988 a festival dedicated to Hurston to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state backed out of its project on the street.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway, they brought what would be said to be high speed, a real pride to the city," Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped to change the city's image of itself.
Those from out of town like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the public historical record in 1998.
A new single-story bookstore (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a repaved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly in Florida: only six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a secondary road in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1800s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to search for Eatonville's story, by its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permit requested in advance is required for most interviews, some things - such as murals on Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a plump teacher, with a penchant for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of city pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston saw his entire race: beautiful, problems and everything, neither better, nor worse and proud, creative, great worker, foolish and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, which he said may need help.
And even those who are younger, such as Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"A lot of people, if they just came in here, they'll think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" said Alondra Kenon after Mass on a recent Sunday.
"But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it's really a pretty city."
