Isabel Bayon rediscovers the Sevillian essence of dancer Tortola Valencia
A Sevillian dancer pays tribute to another dancer equally from Seville.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Florence Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the neighbourhood of Triana, and at the age of three moved with his family to London.
She was a free dance dancer and a specialist in Oriental dances.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of female emancipation, the likes of Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
He was a Buddhist and vegetarian, and defended the cause for the abolition of corset that prevented women from moving freely.
This woman's life, which marked a revolution in dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two wars, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have liked to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me. It seemed incredible to me."
She said: "We don't pretend to tell her whole life, but to gather the spirit of it.
The titles of his dances suggested some basic elements of flamenco.
Thus, "la danza de la mariposa" suggested to me a guajira, or "la danza de la serpiente" some tangos.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my dancing style also fits into this aesthetic," she explains.
The staging includes two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of her shows, as a face in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with what had been a student of hers.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I am happy because he has agreed to work in my work and for this I feel very honored."
The set-up also includes the musical composition and guitarists such as Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi of Moran; the percussions of El Pajaro, as well as the viola of Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Juarez "who plays the role of eternal accompanist of these artists who have been all-round divas, and who have always had many."
In the work there is also in some form the life of this woman who takes place in distant places, particularly for that era, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all of Europe, since, habitually, she resided in London.
"I wanted to remember her, because I think she's one of the women who's had a huge influence in a given historical period and now no one remembers her and much less considers her work as something of value," Bayon says.
The show will begin today, at 8.30 p.m. at the theater of Lope de Vega.
