Repeated drivers of alcoholism will have to install the "alcoholock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol, install in his car the system that prevents the driving of the vehicle in a state of intoxication or if you do not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Attorney General, according to which it will be a pilot project lasting one year.
The purpose of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course at the road.
This initiative, in addition to the General Public Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, will be attended by the Directorate General of Traffic (DGT) and the Technological Institute Foundation for Automobile Safety (FITSA).
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists reported more than once per drunk driving then return to driving the car.
Alcoholock would avoid this, because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the rate of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher concentration of alcohol is detected than allowed.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices allow to reduce up to 65% of infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out on an ordinary basis, and, no doubt the necessary reform for criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a PSOE initiative in which it is proposed to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
