Talking in Sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who talk by staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you take a scare, but it doesn't really matter much.
It is a benign alteration of sleep termed somniloquy.
It manifests with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once in the month ...), the next day the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason for this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, nocturnal enuresis (wetting in bed), or sleepwalking, but that is not necessarily the case.
As already mentioned above it can be associated with stages of very high fever, situations of stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a phenomenon not yet studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, cries, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet to the situation.
We said that this is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, when coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done, on the other hand, is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcite the baby before it goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sleeping pills appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing that happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's asleep and so he's resting.
Remember that if it appears very distressed and episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not see what he is dreaming to say it, so you have to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which it could lead.
