The meeting - Blood is safe again
The Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as the Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most of all, it regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the infected blood scandal in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and population protests, the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation in February 1994, directed by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Society of Blood) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its own business, just 38% of people said they still had faith in the donation system in Quebec, Dr Décary recalls.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood draws and field research over the following years, we have regained public confidence," he explains before proudly stating that by the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Héma-Québec by now.
Dr. Décary, however, is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells the one who has been president since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we absolutely did not know if that disease could be transmitted by infected blood.
There is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when there are doubts and a serious disease could result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which manifests with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for some years now, it has been shown that without any doubt this disease is transmitted by infected blood.
This episode has thus shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow the presence of the virus to be directly recognized in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the same, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs made it possible to reduce the window period, i.e. from the time the person contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
It was possible to reduce that period to a duration of less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and thus not being able to detect them has thus greatly decreased.
These improvements have considerably decreased the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is detected.
I believe that today one can feel calm about receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to having safe resources, the Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
"Necessities increase as the population ages.
As cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors which on average makes up only 3% of Quebecers acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who are 18 years of age and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they get older and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and incite them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that you hardly find an hour to donate blood," says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Héma-Québec which manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is an abundance of stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants early next year," points out Dr. Décary who describes this practice of cord blood sampling as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", as Héma-Québec does not have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
