Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice-president director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world's largest gold company has filed a six-million libel lawsuit against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house with the intention of starting a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a libel lawsuit, but the law.
Without any surprise, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to hers.
No matter the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a substantial amount of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these unequal arms struggles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that gags the opposition as well as frightening anyone who dares to speak out again on the matter.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that she should have presented her own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada normally take place by exchange of views and not by baton strokes.
It would therefore have been enough for society to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to have too much faith in public opinion and badly rejects petitions and letters in support of Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is clearly evident?
In the vice-presidential world, it seems that this word only indicates the handsomely paid lawyers and not the Canadians as a whole; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even disparagers have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn't understand – or doesn't want to understand – is that the public supporting the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of opinion, and not in the light of what many perceive as some sort of gait (searching for the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum instructing them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver's surreal discourse, the Barrack Gold lawsuit constitutes a direct attack on university research freedom and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in every democratic society.
It denies en bloc the right to citation of authentic sources and debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss inconvenient topics for the world's richest companies, under penalty of multiple lawsuits, who can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific standards as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have the right to reply.
