Operation - Wall Street bailout – Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, representatives of the Republican and Democratic side, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the biggest financial-saving plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan, which aims to curb the financial crisis that has been on Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by the two houses of Congress.
It provides in particular: checks on its actual implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of homes foreclosed for non-payments, as well as a right of inspection on remuneration paid to managers of protected companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an effective agreement on the markets," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
"Every decision was made in such a way as to safeguard the American economy and people from the crisis currently taking place on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It's the crucial point: if we hadn't acted this way, priceless confoundings and upsets would have spilled over into the daily lives of Americans," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The cut-off time was the opening of the markets this morning.
Joined later in the negotiation, the two candidates for the US presidential election were quite supportive of the agreement, without however avoiding expressing their discontent with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama deserves credit for adding some provisions to the agreement, particularly that which will allow owners to maintain their domicile and that inherent in wages intended for executives of businesses covered by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice in.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American TV screen.
Interviewed on another channel to find out if he will vote in favor of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details of it, but I hope so."
"According to what I've read, this is something that we all need to digest and that will allow us to move forward"
The option of a non-intervention is simply unacceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back the dubious, risky, and unsellable claims of American financial institutions with taxpayer money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a housing bubble that led firstly to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (mortgages), then to extend to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and result in the freezing of liquidity and the disbandment of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of incumbent Republicans who blew up the first draft of a deal last week.
It seems to have come out of that dead end since Democrats agreed that the active "toxic" of some struggling companies is only being protected by the government, rather than bought.
In order to meet everyone in Congress, a provision has been added that if the government were to face losses over the next five years because of such a program, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion to which 100 billion more can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of 350 billion should be ratified by a further vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the protected companies that will be worth the dividends in case of profit and that he can resell when the waters have calmed down.
According to the plan, the federal government will have the opportunity to delay foreclosure procedures relating to real estate loans and to set limits on remuneration and starting allowances paid to the managers of the companies involved.
As of today, the plan's architects would like to submit it to the House of Representatives vote, and to the Senate vote on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be given the go-ahead.
In fact, there were several votes against the project yesterday, both at the Republican and Democratic sides.
"Clearly, Washington doesn't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But don't take advantage of the taxpayers..
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents the situation differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel Laureates, have written to us to say : we ask Congress not to draw hasty conclusions and to examine carefully the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again a test of the world nature of the crisis.
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for €11.2 billion (US$16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary when the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would give up the purchase of its competitor, in full bankruptcy after the loss of 2 billion euros (2.9 billion dollars) for the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis has 85 000 employees and is part of the twenty largest banks in Europe and the ten largest insurers.
"It's not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, influence and voting rights are collected in banking matters.
It's certainly something that savers and families appreciate now that times are announcing uncertain."
During this period, at the other end of the English Channel, the British government seems to be on the verge of nationalizing another bank poised for the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take charge of all the loans currently under way at Bradford and Bringley bank, of which more than 41 billion (75.5 billion dollars) of real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will be buying the UK bank's branches and customer accounts.
Since the beginning of the economic crisis Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to undergo a process of nationalization by the British government.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a Busy Icon
Blue-eyed beauty was for a long time his ace in the sleeve, for others his weak point.
Did he get rid of the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with a bewitching smile?
Yes and no.
His discretion, sensitivity and evident talent would expel him from that circle of powerful consecrated to real sacred monsters.
What a constancy!
Paul Newman, who passed away on Friday at the age of 83, at his Connecticut ranch, following lung cancer, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the gloomy years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of which he was for a long time a sort of rival on the screen, more prudent in his play, certainly more fragile, but also a spokesman for freedom and the development of dramatic convictions.
Magical children are often born from mixed couples.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and mother of Hungarian origin.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
A humble ego, the ultimate mark of quality.
Because he recognized himself as a country enamored with the safe made man, the Pacific war fighter, proud in combat, who in the early 1950s studied dramatic art at Yale, he subsequently attended the Actor Studio in New York, before triumphing at the theatre, on television and soon at the cinema.
That same militant civil rights man was also the racing driver who ranked second at the 24 Hours of Mans in 1979, as well as sex symbol, though part of a model pairing since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
The shadow zones of a reserved, discreet, committed star, allergic to the scandals of show-business, of which it will never be possible to completely reveal the mystery, go away with him.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the term.
This weekend Paul Newman's disappearance was a heart-pounding blast for cinephiles, while his great characters populate the black screen of memories.
Over half a century of American cinema in full transformation is re-proposed through its interpretations.
They are confused in memory by Butch Cassidy's charming cow-boy (1969) and that boy unable to desire his fiery wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Hot Roof Cat adapted by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
More recently, we remember him as the sensitive Mr. Bridge (1990), troubled by a marriage that did not keep what was promised.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Up there someone loves me, by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean and revived after his death, which officially launched Newman in 1956.
That cute villain in the excellent Stangata, Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiards player in Robert Rossen's The Sweep, a magnificent film (1961), Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him the only Oscar out of 9 nominations in 1987.
That face through the years, it was his.
Him again.
The epochs succeed each other through its path.
Young people know him best for George Roy Hill's cult movie Slap Shot (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in Mr. Hula Hoop, of the Coen brothers.
The circle had ended with one last role as the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Era my father, in 2003.
Unlike the more graded film legends who soon abandoned the trade, Newman will remain in theaters for a long time, denouncing Hollywood in all its pomp, parties and concessions.
Bertrand Tavernier, a French filmmaker, called him, with a hint of irony, "a living challenge to underplaying", judging his performance exaggerated.
The profession was not always a game for the handsome Paul Newman, to whom the roles seemed to fall like manna from the sky.
However, he often preferred the role of the marginalized to that of the young actor: neurotic, alcoholic carrion or desperate characters, of which he expressed disarray and rebellion with his perfect traits.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown nuances of his true, modest sensibility.
Jennifer's first time, in 1968 (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with her wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a subtle female portrait of melancholia.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated to him in 1984 the film Harry and Son, a discreet and sad film.
Among the countless tributes rained on Newman yesterday, his great friend and old comrade in arms Robert Redford (they had acted together in La Stangata and Butch Cassidy) stated with infinite sadness "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity and love of life, two great characteristics of the missing actor.
Beyond a career as a legend, a great militant for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the Hollywood drift, is thus extinguished.
We will have seen her face stand out on bottles of vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging her a bad taste choice, although born as a gag.
The revenue from those sales was, however, earmarked for his Foundation for Children in Trouble.
Newman, instead of resting on his myth, chose to commit himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter saying "Always and until the end, your father was incredibly grateful to his good star .
Being there was a privilege."
And just as privileged it was for us to follow the path of such a clear and generous American artist.
Citizen model, then, and much more.
