The Psychology of Excess Litigation: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists researchers at the University of New York have managed to discover the neuro-economic basis of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study appearing in the journal Science men do not want to fall behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are available to pay even a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "game" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lotto, the other group of players participated in an auction while with the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to licit more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex enters intensively into operation when losing to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price rise is explained by avoiding the vehement reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group carried out a financial pursuit investigation.
In this investigation, three groups litigated against one partner under different conditions.
The control group reported what the real value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group besides this they have promised that in the case of winning they will receive another prize of $15.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose the money in the event of an auction loss.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the winning was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
Comproving the neurologists hypothesis the members of the group that played "against loss" were willing to make higher stakes of the control group or "winning".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These in fact so far explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have come to a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to seek medical attention?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is mentioned among the top causes of death in Hungary.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many sufferers do not know that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver disease caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For travelers it is useful to vaccinate against virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots are formed on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the feces become clear and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most severe variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause cirrhosis of the liver and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, the prevention and carrying out of regular medical analyses is very important.
This disease is much more frequent than average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, addicts and tattooed.
Worldwide, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since a routine laboratory examination also reveals the disease it is worth contacting your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 worldwide by disease associations.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University performed an interesting experiment, examining how faith in god affects the sensation of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out to 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while everyone watched a painting depicting the virgin Mary.
Based on the results, Catholic believers were able to fend off much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first of a series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University take part in addition to academics.
The test took place exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with the ermine by Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the virgin Mary would give rise to a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's picture was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a tranquilizing effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time aro received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics have reported that the vision of the virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care" of them and "they became tranquilized and were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image they accounted for 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work before them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but one must find the suitable image.
"We have to look for an image towards which they have very positive feelings, like a mother or a father" - said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the result of the search.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it manages to change our personality." - added Wright.
After the excellent results only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On their 10th birthday, Google can claim to be in people's pockets as well as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, what clinic they attend and what they care about.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's directors, this is still not enough.
What is concerned with skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they just don't see the substance of web 2.0.
Recently Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times that Google's main purpose is to collect as much personal data as its users and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google's founders that was: "we put all the information in the world into a system!".
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt replied: he would love it if Google could answer questions like "what do I do tomorrow?" or "what would be the right job for me?", but software can't answer seemingly simple questions because they don't know enough about users.
Not all internet users are aware that during their searches on the internet exactly the words searched are recorded, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search started two years ago users can store their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked, these then in the long run will generate much better tailored results; on this same logic it is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our previously stated and recorded preferences.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I'm dealing with? - they ask concerned users of Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, Internet users' counter-reactions are provoked by the fear of the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion to power.
However, a fact is confirmed that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of internet users.
The most striking example of this in recent times has perhaps been the coordinated action against Brazil's pedophiles, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users worried about personal rights instead sighed for relief in May when the firm - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully demonstrated the truth in court against the FBI: even later you cannot force Google with any point in the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government successfully ripped off nearly 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to get the search lists of individual users and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who fear to provide their personal data lash out at Google because they believe that in this way their intimate sphere and private life is affected by starting to use its services and rise with the rebellion due to the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users appearing in numerous countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", as opposed to their rival, Microsoft liquidated as conqueror of the world because of Windows, as much as they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code kept up to date and the package of programs is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies just one of the most often repeated keywords in recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can link them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all of these can insert them into systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, he can also write blogs on which his most recent photo galleries stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
Meanwhile, we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the common tour of friends, easily learns with whom she spent the night her treacherous boyfriend or a company can fire one of her employees because she wrote a sincere opinion on the top of the company: one thing is sure, the concept of private life has now completely reconsidered.
