The intelligent machine mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What could be the best method to develop anti-collision technologies other than mimicking the obstacle sensors found in nature?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan the hornets gave the initial strategic cue to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic minicar equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate aim of creating a system capable of avoiding all collisions.
Flying bees form their own personal oval space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR and R&D technology at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's view, capable of a 300 degree view in each direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the bee's movements, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, differently from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
"If not, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is considered currently inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scavenge other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter, high-energy-density lithium-polymer batteries, which means that their life span is longer than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the instantaneousity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some inputs in seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
You don't need a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, they predict at Nissan, within 10 years can be installed on standard vehicles.
Further possibilities of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles present on the road leads to the destination.
