Mp3 Readers Under Accusation, Put Hearing at Risk
Listening to loud music over an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a statement released in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (Crsseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day holding the apparatus at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I'm concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels can unconsciously damage their hearing beyond repair," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings - continues the EU manager - a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they originated.
"Scientists - concludes the EU executive - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related equipment".
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but concerns are growing as to the auditory damage that may result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
You can greatly limit this damage by resorting to solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music equipment if they listen to loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the limits currently in force concerning the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of the users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
