The Endangered Elites
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
The New York Times confirmed this yesterday by informing us that the ongoing crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old soul East Coast, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance, strong especially in the States of Central and South.
The soul, in fact, that has made itself overwhelmingly alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
This just mentioned is, however, only an example of the changes, of the great changes, that the ongoing economic earthquake perhaps heralds or already lets us see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
In both the US and Europe, the crisis seems to be functioning as an accelerant of long-incubation phenomena and in the new climate they solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual state-sovereignty category in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, yes, close ties with foreign countries, but that first of all see the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state, involved to a very large extent.
Which immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically worldwide but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of the question or not to have much to say: the glaring evidence is given by the European Union which, divided as usual between different interests and between different state strategies, fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the disbursement of funds: since when you get to the corner it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back together.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely connected to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will instead have to deal increasingly with those very immaterial things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place of the earth to another but are still absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So that those who find themselves to be sovereign, certainly possess several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty which, however, foreshadows a fracture.
Those who say Territory, State, Government, inevitably say Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand for someone who can take matters into their own hands.
On the other hand, a wave of disrepute for existing leaderships, especially economic ones, turned out to be so inadequate and full of shadowy areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and somewhat disturbing: a discredit, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of countries in the West.
That is to say, the belief seems to be growing, in vast sectors of the population, that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites so far in vogue, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanly feeds a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which is manifested in the sudden electoral "revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and very last times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of Italy).
One gets the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, are increasingly struggling to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis invigorates, increases, and potentially shakes beyond measure.
In the face of all this talking about a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes wide open certainly isn't at all.
The superglue for walking on walls
Defeat the laws of gravity with super glue and in the future walk on the walls like Spiderman.
It is the goal of several American research centers and now a team of four institutes has gone very close to it.
With a sticker of only 2.5 square centimetres the scholars managed to glue a body of 100 kilograms on a vertical wall.
THE STUDY – The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from Dayton University, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of scholars is an evolution of existing ones using a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that manage to ensure perfect adherence to the animal.
Tests conducted on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time "it easily detaches from the wall" explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the Engineering faculty of the University of Dayton.
WALKING ON THE WALLS? -"This material could be useful as a transient adhesive" adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls just like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
For the time being, no superheroes.
OTHER RESEARCH – The University of Berkeley, California, is also researching a new sticker.
In an article in the journal of the American Chemical Society, Californian scholars presented an adhesive formed of microfibers like hair that self-cleans itself from dust during movement on a surface to always maintain perfect adherence.
Drugs: Never with fruit juices
Beware of grapefruit juice, orange juice, and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in summer because they are thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, when taken at the same time as some life-saving drugs alter their absorption by amplifying or decreasing their effectiveness depending on the case, with even serious consequences for health.
Reiterating the risks of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with taking certain medicines David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, who from the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society underway in Philadelphia launches a new alarm: a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice is enough to reduce the absorption of some life-saving drugs, nullifying their beneficial effects and putting patients' health at risk.
Grapefruit juice was already under indictment because it was held responsible for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, antihistamine and neurological medicines to levels deemed toxic.
FARMACI A RISK - The Italian Medicines Agency itself had given notice of this in an information bulletin two years ago alerting doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger resulting from this mix and to be careful what they drink in case they take drugs such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT ONLY POMPELM - According to experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that inhibit drugs.
Along the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the department of pharmacology of the State University of Milan:"These discoveries are generally immediately reported to the various international and national drug agencies that possibly provide to change the information notes of the drugs.
So always read the illustrative leaflets of the medicines you take and if there is anything that is not clear to us, do not be impressed but ask the doctor or pharmacist for clarification," the expert pointed out to the Ansa agency.
