The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the great Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the suburbs of large multi-salts and the consequent death by consumption of mono-salts in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear to us inescapable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical and memory-laden places,"it is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of road and many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall and nostalgia for a way of living cinema lost perhaps forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the main association of exhibitors, are clear: in the last five years 316 cinemas of traditional type have closed, and to pay the highest price are mainly cinemas in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to show that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multiplex cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally", observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures are built but the survival of those already existing should be guaranteed, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of allocation for the fund in favour of the operators: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not comply with existing laws.
To support the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros per year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, has decided to run to the shelters with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote the cinemas monosala both in the historic center and in the suburbs.
Among the rules are tax relief measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
«It is an initiative that I like» remarks Giuseppe Tornatore"and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
It is certain, however, that in order to counter the overwhelming power of multiplexes traditional halls must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, there where I have experienced so many shared emotions, not to see the billboards blackened by the dust I turn to the other side".
Ties between politics and 'ndrangheta arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was available to standardize the choices of the Municipality to the interests of the Piromalli cosca".
The charges are heavy that the magistrates of the Anti-Mafia Directorate of Calabria address to the mayor and deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and to the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external competition in mafia association.
In handcuffs also Gioacchino Piromalli, the elderly mediator between the clan and the public administrations, and his nephew lawyer, namesake of the boss, already convicted of association for mafia crimes, sentenced to compensate 10 million euros.
"In defiance of any legal and moral norms, as well as common sense", the prosecutors write, the two local administrations had expressed a willingness to pay advice to the lawyer Piromalli.
"It would have been thus granted to the cosca - write the judges - to officially enter the municipalities facilitating the possibilities, already large, of control and direction of the public administration".
The president of the Calabrian regional junta Agazio Loiero does not hide that "collusions between local authorities and organized underworld there are several" in his region: "There are areas where the mafia intensity is stronger than in others, where collusion is almost inevitable.
But there are so many local politicians who resist the pressures of 'Ndrangheta, heroes who keep themselves clean."
The arrests this morning follow those of last July with which the police announced that they had beheaded the Piromalli gang.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro was dissolved but already in 1991, and again due to alleged conditionings between organized crime and local administration, local politicians had been relieved of the task of administering the Municipality.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, mayor of the UDC at the time of the dissolution, had been elected to head a centre-right coalition, after the May 2006 ballot.
He shouted at the scandal when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the city council.
He called in the then Deputy Minister of the Interior Marco Minniti, accusing him of having planned the whole thing for a political issue, but the judges, in the arrest order signed this morning, explain that the Piromalli cosca had even come to ask for the variation of the project of the A3.
From the environmental interceptions ordered against Dal Torrione, the PMs write, it emerged "the willingness to marry the needs of an entrepreneur, representative of a larger group known to be close to the Piromalli, uniforming the choices of the public administration to the interests of the cosca".
When the energy is born from the waves now the big ones come into the field
It is an exterminated field, occupying over 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources they've got their eyes on, and now they're trying to get their hands on, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of deriving energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalist demands and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be covered by sea swell exploitation facilities.
This amount would be twice that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be currents and tides.
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in Northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years on from betting on marine energy are more and more and among these companies always devoted to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies," a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the economic newspaper Wall Street Journal, "and is considering cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to start a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
It is a signal not small, especially considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has started a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron there are New York's Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey's Ocean Power to go down the road of energy coming from the sea and the sums invested so far, though not known in detail, indicate a rising interest according to observers.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not dispel all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the buoys to move up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders within the floats.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent ashore through submarine cables.
For now there are four such plants being designed, pending only federal approval and some of the energy could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water when there are tides causes the turbine blades to spin, creating a rotating motion that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electricity Research, deserves the potential of the tides at this time.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others bordering the coast, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 and planned investments of up to $35 million for 2009.
